				<p>
					Sometimes it is not obvious that factoring will be helpful to solve an equation. However, after a little manipulation we see that many equations can be solved using factoring as the critical step.
				</p>

<example>
				<statement>
					Solve <me>\frac{2}{x} - \frac{2}{x-3} = 3.</me> 
				</statement>	
					
<solution>					
It is not obvious that this would lend itself to factoring. All we can do is proceed with manipulations we know are allowed, and hopefully we reach a point where we can solve. 

<md>
<mrow> \frac{2}{x} - \frac{2}{x-3} = \amp\ 3</mrow>
<mrow>  \updownarrow \amp (\text{combine fractions on left})</mrow>
<mrow> \frac{2(x-3)-2x}{x(x-3)} = \amp\ 3 </mrow>
<mrow>  \updownarrow \amp (\text{simplify numerator on left})</mrow>
<mrow> \frac{-6}{x(x-3)} = \amp\ 3 </mrow>
<mrow>  \updownarrow \amp (\text{clear the denominator}) </mrow>
<mrow> -6 = \amp \  3x(x-3) </mrow>
<mrow>  \updownarrow \amp (\text{distribute and rearrange the equation})</mrow>
<mrow> 3x^2-9x + 6  = \amp\ 0 </mrow>
<mrow>  \updownarrow \amp (\text{factor})</mrow>
<mrow> 3(x-1)(x-2)  = \amp\ 0. </mrow>
</md>

 Now, by the Zero Factors Theorem, we have the solution <m>x=1</m> and <m>x=2</m>. 
				
</solution>
</example>

